4mz.title: Stabiliser (of a group action)
4mz.clickbait: If a group acts on a set, it is useful to consider which elements of the group don't move a certain element of the set.
4mz.text:
[summary: The stabilizer of an element $x$ under the action of a group $G$ is the set ([4lt actually a subgroup]) of elements of $G$ which leave $x$ unchanged. ]

Let the [-3gd] $G$ [3t9 act] on the set $X$.
Then for each element $x \in X$, the *stabiliser* of $x$ under $G$ is $\mathrm{Stab}_G(x) = \{ g \in G: g(x) = x \}$.
That is, it is the collection of elements of $G$ which do not move $x$ under the action.

The stabiliser of $x$ is a subgroup of $G$, for any $x \in X$. ([4lt Proof.])

A closely related notion is that of the [4v8 orbit] of $x$, and the very important [4l8 Orbit-Stabiliser theorem] linking the two.
